THE GPTWA IS WELL-POSITIONED TO PROVIDE CLIMATE ADAPTATION SERVICE IN THE NORTH ENTRAL REGION AND TO GROW THE SCOPE OF THE WORK TO PARTNER WITH ALL SECTORS OF THE 32 FEDERALLY RECOGNIZED TRIBES IN THE REGION. THIS WILL BE DONE IN COORDINATION WITH THEIR CURRENT CRLBY BUILDING OFF ALL THE WORK BEGUN, BY BRINGING ON ONE ADDITIONAL LIAISON AND INTERNS AS FUNDING ALLOWS, AND UTILIZING RESOURCES AT THE NC CASC.OJECTIVE 1- OUTREACH AND EDUCATIONOBJECTIVE 2- SUPPORT FOR PLANNING AND ACTION (FURTHER DEVELOP NETWORK AND IDENTIFY GAPS IN SUPPORT)TARGET GOAL: AN INCREASED NUMBER OF REPS FROM TRIBAL NATIONS (50%) THROUGHOUT THE REGION TO ENSURE BROAD KNOWLEDGE OF THE LIAISON POSITION, CREATE AWARENESS, AND DEMONSTRATE OPPORTUNITIES FOR COLLABORATION.OBJECTIVE 3- FACILITATION AND STRATEGIC NETWORKINGTARGET GROUP: ALL TRIBAL NATIONS PARTICIPATIG IN OBJECTIVE 2 ACTIVITIES, AND ANY OTHERS ENGAGED IN CLIMATE RESILIENCE RESEARCH/ACTION IDENTIFIED IN OBJECTIVE 1.OBJECTIVE 4- PERSNAL PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT AND CAPACITY BUILDINGTARGET SKILLS: SCIENCE COMMUNICATION BOTH ORAL AND WRITTEN, LARGE GROUP FACILITATION FOR CLIMATE ADAPTATION PLANNING AND SCENARIO PLANNING.

THE OBJECTIVES OF THIS PROPOSAL ARE TO IDENTIFY AND HIRE A SENIOR AND AN ASSISTANT BIA TRIBAL CLIMATE RESILIENCE LIAISON WORK WITH THE 35 TRIBAL NATIONS, FEDERAL AND STATE AGENCIES, AND CLIMATE RESEARCHERS ACROSS THE MW CASC REGION REGARDING TRIBAL CLIMATE SCIENCE AND ADAPTATION PLANNING NEEDS, IMPROVE OUTREACH AND TRIBAL CAPACITY BUILDING, IDENTIFY AND ADDRESS RESEARCH GAPS IN CLIMATE, NATURAL AND CULTURAL RESOURCES DISCIPLINES THAT WILL GUIDE STRATEGIC ADAPTIVE PLANNING AND IMPLEMENTATION OF TRIBAL RESILIENCY PROJECTS, HELP DEVELOP SCIENCE AND TOOLS TO MEET TRIBAL NEEDS, AND ADVISE THE NEXT GENERATION OF TRIBAL CLIMATE LEADERS. ALL OF WHICH WILL BE OVERSEEN BY THE CMN SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT INSTITUTE AND SUPPORTED BY THE MW CLIMATE ADAPTATION SCIENCE CENTER.  IN THIS PROPOSAL, THE TENTATIVE WORKPLAN AND TIMELINE FOR THE PROPOSED FIRST YEAR OF WORK FOR THE LIAISON(S) IS INCLUDED AND INTENDED TO START ONCE A COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT IS ESTABLISHED BETWEEN THE COLLEGE OF MENOMINEE NATION AND THE DEPARTMENT OF INTERIOR BUREAU OF INDIAN AFFAIRS. SEMI-ANNUAL REPORTING WILL ALSO OCCUR DURING THE TIMELINE OF THE PROJECT INCLUDING A NARRATIVE REPORT WITH A SUMMARY OF EVENTS, ACCOMPLISHMENTS, PROBLEMS, AND RESULTS DURING THE YEAR, AND A FINANCIAL REPORT.  SDI PARTNERSHIPS, NEW AND CONTINUING, ARE ALSO SUPPORTED IN THE PROJECT. CURRENT PARTNERS INCLUDE THE GREAT LAKES INDIAN FISH & WILDLIFE COMMISSION (GLIFWC), INTER-TRIBAL COUNCIL OF MICHIGAN INC. (ITCMI), 1854 TREATY AUTHORITY, UNITED SOUTHERN AND EASTERN TRIBES (USET), THE NORTHERN INSTITUTE OF APPLIED CLIMATE SCIENCE (NIACS), GREAT LAKES INTEGRATED SCIENCES AND ASSESSMENTS (GLISA), AND THE INSTITUTE FOR TRIBAL ENVIRONMENTAL PROFESSIONALS (ITEP). NEW PARTNERSHIPS ARE ALSO FORMING AMONG THE FOND DU LAC TRIBAL AND COMMUNITY COLLEGE, THE BAY MILLS COMMUNITY COLLEGE, AND THE LAC COURTE OREILLES OJIBWE COLLEGE.

FOR THIS PROJECT, USET'S CLIMATE CHANGE PROGRAM WILL BUILD UPON ITS WORK PROVIDING TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND TRAINING ON CLIMATE RESILIENCY TO MEMBER TRIBAL NATIONS, THROUGH SUPPORTING THE CURRENT SENIOR TRIBAL CLIMATE RESILIENCE LIAISON, AND ADDING AN ASSISTANT TRIBAL CLIMATE RESILIENCE LIAISON. ACTIVITIES INCLUDE DEVELOPMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION OF WORKSHOPS AND TRAINING TO SUPPORT TRIBAL CLIMATE CHANGE RESILIENCE, WHILE CONTINUING TO FOSTER NORTHEAST AND SOUTHEAST CLIMATE ADAPTATION SCIENCE CENTER (NE/SE CASC) TRIBAL ENGAGEMENT IN THEIR RESPECTIVE REGIONS. THIS PROJECT WILL STRENGTHEN EXISTING WORK, WHILE EXPANDING FOREST, WETLANDS, AND RESEARCH ACTIVITIES, ALLOWING US TO EXPAND OUR KNOWLEDGE BASE, CONTINUE TO BUILD OUR COMMUNITY OF PRACTICE ON ISSUES OF CLIMATE CHANGE, AND PROTECT ENVIRONMENTAL AND ECONOMIC RESOURCES IN THE NE/SE CASC REGIONS. THIS PROJECT WILL ALSO BUILD UPON SUCCESSFUL TECHNICAL SUPPORT WORKSHOPS AND TRAININGS THAT HAVE BEEN LED BY THE PROGRAM, NAMELY, USET'S CLIMATE CHANGE VULNERABILITY ASSESSMENT/ADAPTATION PLAN WRITING RETREAT AND USET'S TRIBAL CLIMATE RESILIENCE CAMP. FINALLY, THIS PROJECT ALSO LAYS THE GROUNDWORK FOR FURTHER EXPANSION OF USET'S CLIMATE CHANGE RESILIENCE PROGRAM, WHICH IS ESSENTIAL CONSIDERING THE RAPIDLY INCREASING EFFECTS OF CLIMATE CHANGE ON THE ENVIRONMENT AND THE IMPACT IT IS HAVING AND WILL HAVE ON OUR WAY OF LIFE. SUSTAINABILITY LIES IN PROACTIVE, MINDFUL, AND INTERCONNECTED RESPONSE TO THIS EMERGENCY, IN THE IMMEDIATE AND LONG-TERM.
